@asottile this gives me a crazy idea... what if the cache key used for a `(repo, ref)` was just the sha, and didn't involve the repo path at all?

In practice, a git SHA is unique across all git repositories (yeah okay, I know Google finally found the first sha1 collision, but it took them 110 GPU years of work), so a git SHA could be a decent key. It would mean that the same repository and revision could use the same cache regardless of how you get to it.

Not sure if this is a good idea, especially given that SHA1 has recently been (somewhat) broken. An interesting idea, though :)

@mirca: Can you squash the commits a little? It's fine to have one than one commit per PR (say, maybe 10 or so), but this are a lot and in some cases the commit messages indicate that consecutive commits address the same thing (e.g. "docs" and "most docs"). A smaller number of commits makes it easier for someone who later needs to see how things changed. For that, you don't need e.g. "fix indentation". You could merge that with the previous commit and just pretend that you typed it in correctly in the first place.
Do you know how to interactively squash commits? If not, let me know. 
The most important advice is probably to make a copy of your branch before you do anything, just in case.

