@ilanschnell, thanks for looking into this, and sorry for the confusion.  There are a few issues at play here.

1) The pyferret issue occurs on Linux, not on Windows.  I understand what the behavior *should* be, but it seems the subcommand stuff isn't working the way that it should.  That error message I copied here shows that the entry point is working at a fundamental level, and that argparse is working to some extent, but the subcommand to do the linkages inspection is not working.

2) Windows is a separate issue, brought on by my alternative approach to use setuptools entry points, installed by pip.  I wanted setuptools entry points only as something to try other than conda/conda-build entry points.  I switched to them when I was able to make conda-build work with them.  I know that the .pth mess that setuptools entry points create is not desirable at all.  That's why I use Pip to install these packages (rather than ```python setup.py install```.  It takes the setuptools entry point information, but creates sane entry points like conda/conda-build do.

We have discussed this at length internally.  @mcg1969 is very hesitant to change anything about how features work.  There's a lot of pain there, and his opinion is that it's very hard to anticipate any potential breakage from this PR.

What he would prefer to discuss is how we can prevent incompatible software from being installed together at all.  What metadata could have been recorded to prevent this?  Conda-build 3 will help somewhat with dynamic pinning, but the nature of the issue is deeper than what conda-build currently records.

