@nullscc By "thread-local case" i mean single-threaded without [cooperative multitasking|https://github.com/Yelp/py_zipkin#using-in-multithreading-evironments], e.g. asyncio. If you are in this situation, you can just let py_zipkin propagate context for you via thread-local.

If you are using either multiple hardware threads or multiple green threads or whatever, you need to explicitly pass context. This is why we have the `context_stack` override, and you'll need to use it if you are in a multithreaded environment.

So what i was proposing was that we can have the decorator inject the context into the argument to make it a bit easier to use. btw, I totally ripped this idea off of go: https://blog.golang.org/context

