As far as I understand the MUTF8 coding, this should be a Java code that produces this string:
```
class Str{

    public static void main(String args[]){

        String x = "\u0000\u007f\u00ad\u0600\u061c\u070f\u1680\u180e\u2000\u2028\u205f\u2066\u2067\u2068\u2069\u206a\u3000\ud800\ufeff\ufff9\ufffa";

        System.out.println(x);
    }
}
```

You can compile it and it will work fine...
As it matches the UTF16_size in the dexfile (both 22), I suspect this is the actual output we want somehow...

The question is further: Internally, no decoding/encoding is required to work. Everything you need to do is to call mutf8.decode and you have a unicode aware string that will work internally. The problem is always that you like to print the string somehow, somewhere... Then the question is how we should proceed with such strings. What is the wished outcome? In my opinion, the string should look like as it was a Java string, i.e. with 2 byte unicode escape sequences: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-3.html#jls-3.3

So the question is, if this resulting string should maybe only include chars from the ASCII table - i.e. everything that can be printed in ascii will be printed, and everything else is escaped.
This can be achieved using the `unicode_escape` encoder: https://docs.python.org/2/library/codecs.html#python-specific-encodings
But again here is a small drawback: in py2 a `str` is produced. In py3 a `bytes` object.
Interesstingly, both can now be decoded with `utf-16` and will produce some output (which is also equal in both versions...).

