I think it has to do with the way we qualify integer overflows as false positives. Overflows are not reported unless they change the account state or impact program flow.

If let's say you would also *use* your vulnerable function in an if-statement, the integer overflow would be reported:

```
contract Test {

    function test(uint256 input1, uint256 input2) returns(uint256) {
        uint256 res = input1 * input2;
        return res;
    }

    function useTest(uint256 input1, uint256 input2) returns(bool) {
    	if(test(input1, input2) < 1000) {
    		return true;
    	}

    	return false;
    }
}
```

Or, say you'd save the result in a state variable:

```
contract Test {

    uint256 res;

    function test(uint256 input1, uint256 input2) returns(uint256) {
        res = input1 * input2;
    }
}
```

Does that make sense?

